{"questionId":"14475336","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider a function&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;defined for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;The derivative of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math>&nbsp;is such that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>, for all&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>&nbsp;be the region enclosed by the graph of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math>, the graph of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math>, the line&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;and the line&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;The area of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>27</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the two possible expressions for g(x).</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognizing&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>⇒</mo><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp;(may be seen in diagram/drawing)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>area of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math> is given by subtracting functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> in integral(s)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>±</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mi>k</mi><mo> </mo><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;</strong></em>OR<em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo> </mo><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;</em>OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo> </mo><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo> </mo><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo> </mo><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>±</mo><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mo>-</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mo>-</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>±</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>27</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>±</mo><mfrac><mn>27</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mo>±</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>±</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;</strong></em>AND&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;(accept&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;AND&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"14475336","referenceCode":"23N.1.SL.TZ2.9c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the two possible expressions for g(x).","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between curve and x axis","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.11—Definite integrals, areas under curve onto x-axis and areas between curves"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}